The Czech SSD in Prague doesn't know Voldemort or the pastry shop.
The new members of the ČSSD in the capital will, it seems, have to overcome the obvious language barriers for the members of the Prague Board and the Municipal Council to understand their renewed SDG partners.
Aktuálně.cz period "examined" the members of the new Council of the ČSSD to check their knowledge of the marked slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition governed Prague.
The coded dictionary that used the political flower and cream of Prague during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that new councillors barely understand these familiar concepts.
At least that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I don't know, really".
"I am a beginner in Prague politics", said culture councillor Lukáš Kaucký during the examination of "college" terminology.
And as for the veteran politician, Karel Březina reacted the same way.
You may be familiar with the concept of "golf hood".
"Maybe it's the only expression of all the ones you asked me that I use every now and then".
"If not, I usually don't use slang".
From the glossary, whose definitions were published by Aktuálně.cz last June before the SDG voting congress, the editorial board selected six examples, in particular those that are particularly relevant to the municipal authorities of Prague.
Socialists had to explain the concepts of "Voldemort", "the biggest golf hole in Prague", "going to the pastry shop", "bull neck", "capital betrayal" and "armour".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be in charge of education in Prague in the future, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, refused to do so.
"I don't get into this stuff, and I'm not going to judge how civic democrats have fun".
"What matters to me is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programmes", he said.
As has been seen, it is alleged that the councillor Lukáš Kaucký did not realize that the above title is an expression about an influential businessman and friend of the former mayor of Bém, Roman Janoušek.
Kaucký is not familiar with the word "Voldemort"; the only term he got on the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"It's the Blanka tunnel", Kaucký says, adding immediately: "But I know more about it from the news".
"I'm going to have to take a language course", he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognises the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the environment councillor Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both Social Democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; furthermore, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague", Plachý soon learns that it is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that he got such knowledge from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the test participants, there is no glossary of colloquial terms so familiar among the Social Democrats.
"I asked my colleagues, but it really seems we have nothing in common".
"Rather, we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations, or play word games with names", says the president of the Prague ČSSD, Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call him Hulda.
"In school they called me Březa, but I don't know if my classmates call me that too", confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
Aktuálně.cz has tested the name and it works.
For his partymates, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), the representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they associated before the election during the party sponsorship, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") from some of his colleagues.
The nicknames are also the only expressions that the Social Democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz even discovered other nicknames for this Prague president.
The "Doctor of the Law of Stamp Law" seems to recall that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in Law at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example for health reasons, unmarried and childless.
Women who turn into witches are sent to an isolated area, so as not to harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such otherwise".
"Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help with the work and have children", explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, provides a special home for more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
However, this has a catch.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read", warns Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of writing awareness.
Charges of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, a neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when she was tortured by three women and two men, covered with gasoline and burned.
The news was on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate set of circumstances.
According to her story, the woman caught herself in the oil used for ritual anointing.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" of the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "The human-devours have always been a danger", he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to quell the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic".
"To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly chosen from among the Gambian peoples to the president's property in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a pot of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people detained.
The tenant in Bakala: he warms up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The elderly and sluggish man walked through the doors of the RPG Byty customer service center of "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rented flats in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying documents with the new three-story lease agreements: his own, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving his sentence.
The three of them just caught the rent liberalisation.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-bedroom apartment with a separate second-class kitchen.
"Moreover, it has no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler", the man points out in his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it", he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until 7 December, when it will publish a guide on how to proceed in these cases.
But in the face of this, man only makes a nod.
"Everyone says something", he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great testing ground for liberalization.
After New Year's Eve will be the case for the vast majority of the apartments that were, in the Czech Republic, until now, rented under a regulated lease.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG Mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a number machine.
"Rental 2011", you can read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a little paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It hardly takes time to read "157" and the number is already on the big screen at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple comes to ask, but the crowd in the room isn't here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as they used to: claims for settlements, insurance issues and the like.
Letters with the new lease agreements will arrive in Ostrava in the mailboxes of tenants of most of the 44,000 RPG-owned flats around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in their letters an increase in rent of between 15 and 38%.
On 18 November a special window opens in the customer service centre for new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting", respond workers who are in it after a brief hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalisation and the old miners' floors in Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already treated loud and clear by the deputy speaker of Parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek, from the ČSSD, from Ostrava, and now appear continuously in local newspapers.
"Twenty years later, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change my damn bathroom dish", says the man mentioned in the introduction.
According to the workers, for the time being they come more than anything retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised in the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before 15 December will also receive half the discount on the February rent.
The window of 'liberalisation' of mining certainly fails to dispel the flood of doubt.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for rent in 2011", estimates the window worker.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the parties do not agree on the rental, an independent judge must decide the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely lawful way to proceed", RPG warns on its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here", says one of the employees at RPG Byty and a man in the street in front of the customer service centre gives her at least part of the reason.
"I get a pension of 13,000 and have 5,000 left over for food; I have no means to go to court", he says.
But immediately the employee seeds doubt.
"We'll see about that".
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people wait", he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic by early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic need.
"The current rents still do not even cover the amounts needed to maintain the community fund", recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the RPG Byty company, who adds that the negligent state of the community fund that annoys tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years that ran between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments with rentals, in the four years that will run from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The big screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data highlighted in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties".
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square meter per month", the screen says.
Just a 38% increase in the 400-floor RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter", RPG says.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not hit rentals at once, but will escalate between four to eight years.
The company will invest all the money raised in the rent (see chart) back into the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to the persons who sign the rental agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything in it: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, Arch.Design employees' children have been able to visit her.
The architectural project firm Arch.Design, from whose studio many well-known buildings in Brno emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-garden.
The company employs about 90 people, mostly in the baby boom age and they wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after the birth.
Along with the possibility of reduced hours, daycare is one of the benefits Arch.Design offers its workers under its social programme.
Builders and architects can thus combine a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-garden was the idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-garden is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
With the funding granted (over CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-dining facility running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project took one year and the application for funding was submitted by Economy Rating.
The childcare is provided by qualified staff, and a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present throughout the day to care for them.
Since it is a "mini-nursery", it can only accommodate up to five children simultaneously, although with shifts more children come during the day.
The operation of the daycare centre is flexible to meet the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the daycare centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the content of the nursery programme is comparable to the usual preschool programme.
Children not only play there, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, they also teach English.
The classroom not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can visit their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up the children late from school when they are away from their workplace.
This way, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
Arch.Design is thus one of the companies that offer a great advantage for the recruitment of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this programme has strengthened the marketing of staff.
The house of bones is still fascinating after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs look like the back of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its similar shape to a skeleton, locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, striking colours, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and the omnipresent lines gently curved, all are typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The front of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and wildlife.
By paying more attention, you observe a certain geometry, rhythm, and carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
The serpent and the twist of the forms still surprise us inside.
The corrugated wood copies the window frames, the railings, the decorations of the doors, the viewfills, and the signs.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample neighborhood at number 43 of the lively Passeig de Grácia shopping street, was born from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
Architect Josep María Jujol collaborated on the design.
In fact, in his plans for the project, decorations for the property owner's representative apartment and the mosaics used on the facade emerged.
On the facade also other creators and artists work.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Batlló House was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell de Gaudí park, in which other pieces of it are found.
Because of its organic shape, locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began calling it "the house of the yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system in the house with ventilation valves and typical chimneys.
It may seem odd that he's tilted 45 degrees.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the building norms of the time at all and did not let himself be influenced by them.
Nevertheless, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, upon completion, the town hall was so shocked by the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was bothered, for example, by the fact that the building included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the city council's request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The lower floors were built by the owner himself.
In the second floor gallery was the living room and on the third floor were the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading up to the rooftop terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate without problems, without renouncing the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the interior courtyard and lights.
The two-color game provides maximum lighting for every floor of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and full-fledged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the famous creator's birth.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very profitable business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, pensioners and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry of other Gaudi constructions into the city.
If you want to enjoy the real atmosphere of bed with your lizard towers, you should quickly befriend some resident of the neighboring houses and visit them at home.
How to choose a mattress and a dressing room: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous bed frame; what really confers its quality on a good bed is the surface to lie down on, that is, the mattress and the dressing room.
First of all, they must be perfectly complementary to suit the specific users.
During the election, numerous elements come into play, including the weight, height, health status and sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and the dressing room are placed is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "warm up" more slowly.
In addition, they often weigh considerably more than regular polyurethane mattresses.
It is therefore necessary to turn them around more often.
If the central canals are not properly ventilated and, above, are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside.
When choosing a bed, habits also influence.
Those who have spent a long time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
"Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep as well here".
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic".
"These types of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have problems with the nervous system, so they receive poor information about joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in cushioned furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem anymore, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico".
You don't have to be an NHL player to appreciate the viscoelastic anymore.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to its body heat.
Nothing presses; at night, it won't turn like after a hard match.
It just makes him sleep better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman who is about 180 cm tall will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
For single rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when you lie on your face, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk toward your elbows", advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert at Cechu čalouníků a dekoratérů, who has been working for many years on the problem of healthy sleep and furniture ergonomics, a subject she teaches in specialized schools.
In double rooms, each needs its own mattress and dressing room, so when buying, you have to be careful to match the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, the so-swimming will have to be mounted at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, models with a minimum of 15 cm of dwelling interior, of which at least three centimetres are for the layer that adapts to shapes and smoothness.
"When you touch it with your hand or when you sit on the mattress, you should definitely not notice the docks", warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of dressing.
The fully padded bedrooms, where the mattress and base are like Siamese, have no meaning in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and cannot be washed, which is often done today.
And since we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat every night, it's clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will start to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, experts reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
But everything has a but.
That is why sellers advise: On mattresses that are 120 or 140 cm wide, carefully clean and wash the cover, but add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress cases are currently made with a cremator closure all around their perimeter, when they are opened they are left in two parts (something very important for the washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling on larger models (and by one person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a napkin, do you have a firm table?
I never did!
At most for the beds designed to keep the visitors overnight.
However, it should make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes in the table and should be used with a mattress with docks inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the docks in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulating sheet mattresses containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut fibre) may be used, although a mattress with a higher number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the lumbar area sheets are reinforced and its stiffness can be adjusted is always preferable.
Joint sheet sockets should not be used with a spring mattress, as they do not react to reclination.
In addition to the adjustment of the stiffness of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixture on the sheets that allows the sheets to be pressed or even tilted so that they "ride" perfectly around the shoulders during sleep.
For men with very broad shoulders, this is something very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "male" class, began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember the women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For more demanding customers, cross-structured or multi-turned cushioning table suits are available.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the voltage is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and dressing, if you use a bad pillow (large and "mullided"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow must support the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can relax.
The recommended size is 50 x 60 cm, which is normal in Scandinavia, for example.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder-reinforced somier or the softer area of the mattress) as the shoulder height.
Modern mattresses seem to have something to do with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or at least mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are fashionable.
The petroleum-based raw materials used to make polyurethane foam are filled with natural oils, such as castor oil or soybeans.
In fact, almost all known manufacturers use soy.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the centre is made exclusively of natural materials", explains Petr Vašíček of Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh scent into the forest or lavender.
There are also differences between men and women.
While men "cool themselves" with breeze vegetable extracts, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "heat" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel warmer.
Favorites at the moment?
Collars made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold and viscoelastic foam rigidities makes it possible to make mattresses from different areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good-quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT rate, since they are considered to be healthcare.
The first to obtain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It's hard to save on mattresses and napkins.
Sometimes offers from manufacturers or sellers can be approved, sometimes offering two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is free.
The age of viscoelasticity with an open cellular structure and a high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
It originally came about as NASA material, because during takeoffs, astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
The human body, therefore, when warm, exerts a perfect effect and adapts its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal for preventing sores, but also for improving sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses but also for health products, for example pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
For example, domestic manufacturers use Eucatherm C foam or Twinsaver and the like.
More and more parents are using people tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about GPS monitoring.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track people's movements and contribute to the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is roughly the size of a mattress box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the missing Anička case and began to be informed about the available means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading their privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that it is not a spy, but another means to reduce the chances of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases".
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons", adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "coffin" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even the youngest children show great creativity when they deliberately lose certain things if they want to avoid being controlled".
"Previously, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device", says Bočková.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether such a device is actually useful in the event of an attack.
"If it's a prepared kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check whether the child carries some sort of electronic device that can reveal their location".
"Now it's the phone".
"As the use of tracking devices expands, you will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be done with a lot of publicity".
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can be helpful.
"The device can be configured to regularly send the position after a certain period".
"If damaged, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person concerned".
"The most expensive devices have an integrated tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stays still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question", says Čech.
In their view, such a service can be obtained even with navigated smartphones, where only special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they are currently devices with a size similar to a mattress box or smaller mobile phones.
So you can get lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for that reason, tests are currently being conducted with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device".
"Or it will identify him after a certain time, which can buy the police time", he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position verification with a GPS system (used in the usual car navigation) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
