Already last year the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
So they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is, the life of the mecha is two years, four years at most.
The army bought the explosive device from STV Group, a.s. for 40 million crowns.
General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mecha saying that soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of mecha a year.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnics, with whom MF DNES was in contact, it is decided that, in such a case, they should perform such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year as well as all generals, high-ranking officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want exemptions, neither did Minister of Defence Alexandr Vondr nor army captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could the army be justified in spending 60 kilometres of machete.
That's the length of 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough supplies for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of mesh, the army would have with the new purchase (even by adding the consumption of engineers or special units) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained recently to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so they limit even the practice of shooting for money.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also cannot understand that we are repeatedly bought such quantities of mecha".
"But it's their decision and they'll certainly know why they act like this".
"For us, the army is a good customer that we as a company try to satisfy", admits Jan Děcký, commercial director of STV Group.
Defence Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometres of mecha by saying he will also have stockpiles of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of STV Group indicates that the mesh has a shelf life of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four", says one soldier who, because of possible criticism from the army, refuses to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument from the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of mecha, he got a discount.
"We were 60 percent less than last year's order of 244 kilometers", says the spokesman for the Ministry of Defence's shopping centre Pejšek.
Just to compare: the annual consumption of mecha by police firearms, which remove World War II ammunition or the ammunition left behind by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only for the right amount to deplete the ammunition before its useful life ends.
They decided to do this for safety reasons for the pyrotechnics and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of mecha can be obtained.
The Ministry is already having clear difficulties finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics MF DNES spoke to, after a couple of years the following problem with the current one will occur: it will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old mecha, which is now being bought "cheap".
I still live on the contacts I got from the contest.
The fact that he won the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest helped Lukáš Pytloun sell the franchises of his hotel.
The last edition, the 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec won the "Entrepreneur of the Year" competition.
His success story seems to be taken from a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun loved to travel.
Abroad he realized that Liberec needed quality and affordable accommodation.
With the savings he collected from seasonal jobs abroad and a bank loan he bought a half-ruined five-story house.
Considering he was still in his third year of college, he was really brave.
"Today, the quality-price ratio of accommodation in our area has moved me to do something about it", says Lukáš Pytloun.
He started renting the first rebuilt floor to foreign workers.
All the income he earned he re-invested in the building, which gradually turned into a 54-room boarding house.
Since then, in seven years in the business, he gradually managed to open in Liberec four boarding houses, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of around 300 in all accommodation categories.
The most comfortable of them all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year it opened another of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov or Tise, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise", said the number one businessman last year.
"This sale of hotel opening licenses was greatly helped by the fact that we won the 'Entrepreneur of the Year' competition", adds Pytloun.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, they still congratulated me often, and I must say, I was very nice", he recalls.
I would certainly recommend anyone who wants to try out a company that participates in the contest.
But he feels that it is not necessary to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He claims that, so far, he still lives off contacts and acquaintances that, without the contest, he might not have gotten.
"I've started to collaborate regularly with some people I met through the contest".
The fame associated with success, in his opinion, also included in employees,
In total, about seventy.
"I've seen them show greater loyalty and are proud to be involved in something that has gained general recognition".
"It is not, much less, my own personal success, but the result of the hard work of the whole team".
"Only my name is on the front page", says Lukáš Pytloun modestly today.
I wish my successor a calmer year than we had at Farmet.
The euphoria for victory soon dissipated by the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the hard work of the winner, Farmet may have already gone through the worst.
The owner of Farmet, Karel Žďárský, received the first prize at the last edition of Vodafone's "Company of the Year" competition, last year at the Prague "Slavic House".
The jury appreciated his efforts, with which he managed to turn a small technical workshop in Česká Skalice into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
"I can say that the award not only encouraged me, but all my collaborators and improved our confidence in fighting the competition", says last year's winner.
The history of Farmet started with the desire to do something useful.
So when the State offered Karel Žďárský's father the rent of a small workshop as compensation for the blockade of property during the communist era, he did not hesitate too much; he resigned his position at the company where he worked and, with a couple of colleagues, founded the company with his father of plastic batteries.
Soon after, they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
Eight years later they became the largest automated printing press manufacturer in central Europe.
They also gained a greater presence among the non-specialized public after achieving success in the media competition.
"Not only did our customers start to consider the Farmet brand considerably better, but foreign partners also started to value the collaboration with a company that achieved greater success in their country", says Karel Žďárský.
Last year's Farmet may not have been just a taste of the euphoria of victory.
It also gained recognition for trade performance up to 2008 and partly 2009.
And it was 2009 that was the hardest year for selling machinery.
The worsening crisis, which had not yet reached so many citizens, caused companies to halt their investment projects and begin to limit the purchase of new machines or technologies.
"We, of course, are not getting out of that situation either".
"Revenue fell by 40%, we had to limit production and even had some layoffs", explains Karel Žďárský.
A viable company sometimes has to take even unpopular measures.
However, they controlled the situation and kept the company profits even at lower levels than before the crisis.
After all, where Farmet didn't cut spending was in research and development.
"With the grants we have built a research and training centre, strengthened our presence on the international market and obtained excellent ratings at national fairs", says Žďárský.
All indications are that they've already left the crisis behind.
Income is rising again and with it, the number of new employees.
"The new achievement is expected to bring a feeling of victory, but in a calmer atmosphere", says Karel Žďárský.
A survey that uncovers ridiculous standards
The Absurdity of the Year poll is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
You've already gotten rid of some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity of the Year survey was the obligation to bring documents to the administration that officials can access online.
The decision was taken by more than a third of the nearly four thousand voters.
For example, the Social Security Administration requested an extract from the trade register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse moves.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
'The Czech Social Security Administration will no longer request an extract from the commercial register when it checks the insured's taxes,' said Jana Buraňová, spokeswoman for the ČSSZ.
The aim of the Absurdity survey of the year is to examine the rules and regulations that businesses and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it is part of the Hospodářské noviny business tournament for the fourth time and is also starting to attract the general public.
While last year's edition had three thousand voters, this year it almost reached four thousand.
And it's not surprising, since we still have a lot of legal obligations that need to be respected just to trade.
"Perhaps we are world number one in the number of documents needed for tax returns", says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, compared with the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, in terms of the conditions for owning a company, the Czech Republic is in 74th position, which is eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was first held in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can point to some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the competition closes.
Proposals can be submitted on the website www.firmaroku.cz. After that, the organizer of the contest selects seven candidates for the "pre-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote online via www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The one who gets the most votes wins the absurdity.
This year's survey included more than 100 proposals, including 105 nonsensical rules and regulations.
The examples were sent by both businessmen and professional associations and journalists.
Among the finalists of the competition was, for example, the requirement that road and highway maintenance vehicles pay the toll or that employers with 20 employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of 70 proposals for this year is published on the page of the competition.
The announcement of the competition, which is always held in early November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which political and social figures usually participate.
This year, for example, the contest was attended by Eva Svobodová, Director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
"Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the State continually imposes barriers on entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year at least thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade", announced Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not in vain.
In 2007, the most annoying thing was the obligation of the businessman to communicate three days in advance to the business office in the permanent operation area, the intention to take a job to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was abolished in the new industrial law.
The obligation which came second in votes in 2007, namely the communication to the work office by their foreign workers of up to 30 days' work trips, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
And the third is defeated.
The 2009 Absurdity was the regulation for physiotherapists to have a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales in their office.
That is why this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
A new category recognises socially responsible enterprises
Environmental, humanitarian, educational and sport projects are evaluated.
The fifth edition of the Hospodářské noviny competition is a new category, the responsible company of 2010.
The purpose of this competition is to support responsible and fair enterprises.
"We thus want to support companies that are concerned with the impact of their activity on the environment and that support socially responsible activities", says Patrik Bartholdy, regional director of the mobile operator of Vodafone, the organizer and sponsor of the contest, as in the case of the Rebelde of the year.
For this new special subcategory of this year's main competition of Vodafone Empresa 2010, companies were submitted for which commercial success is not the only long-term objective.
The story of each of them is inspiring and would allow us to write a standalone article.
Although the type of activities varies widely between the two, the common denominator is the support and consideration they offer.
In one case, for example, it is the disabled, in others, it is the personal or health problems of the employees.
Among the 14 finalists from across the Republic was, for example, the Prague software company Et Netera, which supports the formation of informal sports teams among its workers, who then participate in various sports tournaments.
Another example of a company responsible for the Pardubice area is the Isolit-Bravo company, which has been the main donor of funds for disabled children for seven years.
In Poděbrad, a paper mill is particularly concerned about the health problems of its workers, who make up more than 70% of the workforce.
In Olomouc he won the accounting firm MiRyz Soft, which reduced working hours, even below the weekly average of 35 hours, without reducing wages.
The title was also awarded because it purchases primarily from Czech manufacturers, supports Community activities in the area and respects the environment.
"We try to recycle as much as possible so that our production and management activities produce the least possible impact on the environment", explains entrepreneur Miluše Ryznarová.
The company responsible for IT Enlogit in the Ústí region also thinks about the health of its employees and, with each laptop, offered them a chair and ergonomic keyboards; in addition, it supports work from home and in its business events uses the catering services of a local protected company.
"We also support the Persona in difficulty scholarship, which helps the local Roma community", says Ondřej Suchý, a company representative.
The company also has a good position, namely the Praní a čištění laundry company in the Karlovy Vary region, whose employees receive special bonuses that affect their pension funds.
"We provide benefits in food, transport, skills improvement and leisure", says Josef Strapáč, of the Bruntál Czasch construction company, a winner in the Moravian-Silesian region.
In the category of responsible company of the year, all regional finalists of the Vodafone Empresa contest of the year who answered the questions on the registration form and sent it to the organizers before 15 August were automatically nominated.
The organisers removed from the evaluation forms that were incomplete or incorrect.
"If the representatives of the competing companies did not answer the questions, they could not participate in the responsible company of the year competition, but they are not disqualified from the 'main' Vodafone company of the year competition".
"Individual applications for this competition are not allowed, as it is a subcategory of the main Enterprise competition of the year", explains Karel Goldman of Bison & Rose.
Police made arrests during a public auction at the Farm Fund building in Pilsen
The anti-corruption police have made several arrests in the Farm Fund building in recent days.
Detectives handcuffed a local media businessman and real estate entrepreneur Luboš G.
It appears that the Commission is attempting to manipulate an ongoing public auction for the refund of the rights in such a way that the auctioned land is given to a specific interested party.
He was to pay Luboš G. half a million crowns for it.
"For the moment I can only say that the police are looking for a person for bribe during a public auction and public tender", said Pilsen's chief prosecutor Antonie Zelená, adding that for the moment she cannot disclose further details about the ongoing investigation.
Twenty-four hours later, the police released the 46-year-old businessman.
How he might have influenced the public auction, given the little official information, is only speculative.
Agricultural Fund spokeswoman Lubomíra Černá answered Právo's questions by saying that the police actually carried out the arrest at Pilsen's headquarters and it was during a public auction.
"This is a client, not one of our workers", he said.
According to Černá, the public auction is called 'Call for the submission of proposals for the transfer of land in accordance with the Land Act' and is held when several interested parties appear in relation to the land offered.
"These persons, during the call, offer a value higher than their restitution, which must be transferred before the value of the land is announced".
"The order of the buyers is determined by the bids and the land is transferred by the Agricultural Fund to the person who offers the highest bid", the Fund spokeswoman explained.
Luboš G. had information on who was to be invited and, since he was also an interested person because he had acquired various restitution rights, proposed to the interested parties in the land that he would not participate in the auction.
For that, he was charging a commission.
That would explain why, at the time of his arrest, he had so much money on him.
