Families will have to pay an extra charge of several hundred crowns a month
From January, households will have to pay not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rent.
As a result, families will have to withdraw several hundred crowns a month from their wallets from January onwards.
Electricity prices rise by 4.6%, gas by about 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 crowns more per year than it is now.
However, the main electricity suppliers lowered prices as support for renewable energy production, in particular photovoltaic, increased.
However, gas is only moderately expensive, especially when heating is used more and consumption is therefore higher.
In this case, they should also have a couple hundred more crowns a year.
As electricity and gas are increasingly expensive across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay from January onwards about 50 crowns a month for central heating, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 crowns a year.
Prague residents will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rent does not change, the Pragueers will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the whole country.
In Northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will be higher by 7.4%.
They can increase the rental prices of 450,000 rented apartments in Prague considerably, where the regulation will end in January.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 apartments in Ústí nad Labem, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to court those who disagree with the new lease.
The regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 apartments, could rise by up to 10% next year.
The young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of 15 to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is based on the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is out of fashion, because it takes too long to get drunk".
"Now the trend is strong alcoholic beverages", says Luděk Pelikán, head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia.
"When you manage to get a bottle of your father's alacena, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka".
"Wodka has the advantage of being lighter with juice and not smelling so bad", she explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum".
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, especially among schoolchildren".
"In some cases, they use watermelon that they took home", adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, it's 13 and 14-year-old drinkers who usually show up in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where she has been working since this year, she worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times".
"It started at the age of 12, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohols in her blood, plus a blend of ecstasy", says the department doctor on this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party".
"The interesting thing is that his mother was not surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours", the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest in alcohol by parents or even their clear tolerance of alcohol by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that in the case of children, dependency cannot be properly discussed.
"An alcoholic is defined as a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children".
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is more because of a systematically failed social or family environment", explains chief Pelikán.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year, forty drunk children were hospitalized in the Motol pediatric clinic until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come with a serious poisoning and should stay in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after a walking medical examination, go home to their parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink water, there are three seasonal ups and downs for Pelikán: Witch Day, End of Year and end of school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad grades or, conversely, celebrate the beginning of the holiday".
"On Witches' Day I have seen up to seven children drunk at a time", Pelikán adds.
Drunken people who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injecting a serum with glucose and nutrients that are lacking in the body.
"These guys are doing much better because after a busy night, they get up well and they don't hurt".
"They only show confusion about where they are", Pelikán notes, adding that patients often lose their good mood at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
The cost of an ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients is tens of thousands of crowns.
"I have often used cost as a means of educating them, when on visiting I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job in order for you to earn enough to pay that night", Pelikán adds.
Health insurance, in your opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually pays back to people the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159s are in private hands for the first time in Spain
Two L-159s out of a total of five, which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced with the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed Tuesday for Seville, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa - EADS is located.
It's the first time such a device has ever been in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
At the time, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
It is the two-seater version L-159T1, which until now was used by the Czech army and was still in flight condition.
The remaining three planes are the L-159 single-seaters.
These are still held at Aer Vodochody and the sales intermediary, Omnipol, took over them last week.
Jan Peješk, from the defense press department, says it's not yet known when the planes will physically withdraw from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seaters, on the other hand, were separated from the repaired aircraft a long time ago, without any additional investment or contribution from the Ministry".
"The two-seater L-159T1 was exchanged in its current state", he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army is not running out of two-seat aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for an amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seaters.
One of the new planes was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS has committed to adding aircraft to the equipment of some Allied countries.
'The contract clearly states that EADS is the company that will withdraw the L-159 aircraft and that they will be used for the piloting practices of NATO countries.'
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this context", Pejšek points out.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published ahead of time that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense management claims that the exchange promotes future L-159 export abroad.
The Czech army has acquired Aer 72 aircraft and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes could potentially have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already complained to the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice that it should choose the aircraft by conducting a European tender and not contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last should arrive at Prague's Kbely airport in fourteen days.
A finger longer than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men with a longer than annular index are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the startling conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer journal.
They could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger may be a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to 60 years of age", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could therefore help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if this trait is associated with genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, according to Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They had the same odds of getting prostate cancer as 19 percent of those with fingers of the same length.
For men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows about the study, but he does not think the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "fully demonstrated".
