The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America and private enterprises continues to increase.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it is possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, which was carried out in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively lively humor that reigns in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the South American Pacific coast (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a 40% drop in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a sharp decline in production last year.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see graph 2).
Around 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy in practice works in their country, the same figure as last year but considerably higher than the 25% recorded in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% said they trusted their country's Congress and 45% their government, the same as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has remained in place during the global financial crisis is probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and has declined again this year, to 32%.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the polls began, more Latin American respondents cite crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see chart 5).
Some 31% say they or a close relative have been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has fallen from 38% last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprises are indispensable for development, compared with only 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of Venezuelan respondents agree (and 80% support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (the same figure as 9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
