An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers have discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it proves that it is possible that life forms exist without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That makes it very peculiar, though little is left to be a truly 'alien' life-form", said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appears in the online edition of Thursday's Science.
For a long time, it was thought that there are six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the find is important for the search for life on different planets than Earth, as researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss the discovery, in which no details were released, generated much speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "does show is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of 'standard' elements we consider indispensable for life may not be as fixed", said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, U.K.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure", Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate between them".
"Arsenic is different enough, however, that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it goes in and, in a way, it calms up the biochemical machinery", Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt to and use to grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a life form that uses arsenic could naturally exist, whether in other parts of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that phosphorus could replace arsenic is not new, but no example had ever been found to prove it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth ages, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
"It does suggest that there might be other ways to generate life, not just the way life formed on Earth in ancient times", said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
