The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said it was "surely pleased" with the decision, which came after an entire year of investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of their investigation and that it has no plans to bring charges against him on this issue".
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign might have conspired to violate a federal criminal lobbying ban.
Interviews, email and other documents first leaked in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, get lucrative lobbying jobs to get Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, silenced about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign's assistant, he was barred under law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute", said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the Ensign decision, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared wary of accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks to its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, amid allegations of procedural misconduct.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards", said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that laws do not apply to them", he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's senior counsel, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign's defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "acted according to the law".
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to prosecutors.
"I don't feel comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it didn't have enough evidence to prove the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got lobbying work thanks to Ensign's help to Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him that he was "crushing" the Home Office over a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and called the transportation secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When news of the affair first came out last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign's spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, she said the senator expected the ethics committee to quickly follow the example of the Justice Department and conclude its investigation.
"Senator Ensign wishes to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada", he said.
Cheshire's appeal will be directed to Twitter
There were half a dozen of them "chattering" in the courtroom.
Minutes to minutes, they sent reports of the appalling testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter posts about the process that addressed the rape and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three family members in Cheshire, Connecticut, is set to come to an official end, with the judge's imposition of the death penalty voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have filed court papers outlining the arguments of the appeals that will likely occupy the courts for years to come.
One of the most provocative claims is that intense reports about the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created "a circus atmosphere", and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details caused public passions to exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The complaint could force the appellate judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
"From what I experienced during this trial, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of new technology in the courtroom is affecting the individual's rights to a fair trial", said Thomas J. Ullmann, senior counsel for Mr. Hayes's defense.
First instance judge Jon C. Blue of the State Superior Court laconically rejected the lawsuits in a ruling last week, saying the news media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But it's probably not the last word on the subject.
For decades, appeals courts have recognized that covering famous cases can raise questions about the impartiality of a process.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in his ruling, in Sheppard v. Maxwell, that there was "a carnival atmosphere in the process" due to the media.
The crime is believed to have been inspired by the TV show and movie "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said that the appellate courts that examined Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later might be intrigued by the argument that new rules might be needed to control the way communication from courtrooms, something unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is a general cause for concern about the impact of new media" on high-profile processes, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied Connecticut's death penalty and wrote a report that said it was imposed arbitrarily.
Professor Donohue said some appellate judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting immediate communication from courtrooms could make judgments fairer.
The Twitter issue is just one of many issues outlined by Hayes' lawyers, which will likely be discussed for years, delaying execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Hayes could have been harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors, showing them spooky photographs of the crime scene during jury selection.
Some jurors have said they were horrified by the photographs of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and their daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge wrongly removed a jury that had criticized prosecutors, and that he had wrongly pressed for a verdict over his strange decision to order the jury to deliberate for a weekend.
The jurors weren't kidnapped.
But his arguments about the effect of the intense coverage of the process can attract most interest.
They noted in a refusal to file a verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continually lit the fire of emotion over the case.
"The daily clustering of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom", the lawyers wrote, "was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps throughout the state".
His attention on Twitter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that complaining about the fact that immediate news was more important than reports delivered more slowly was a ludicrous view that would make the court's policy on control of coverage weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said that appeals courts were often drawn to the arguments about the adaptation required in courts because of social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In their letter, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which overturned Dr. Sheppard's conviction because of the coverage of the trial, and made it clear that they would require that new media would require new rules.
"This case", they wrote, "represents the 21st century Sheppard v. Maxwell case".
Can civilization build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign of invective and negativity, this week has sparked a bit of civility in Washington.
Is this a harbinger of a genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the big issues that must be addressed during the outgoing session.
But by all accounts, it was at least a polite discussion of the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to earn party points.
The public meeting of the President's deficit committee on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a testing period, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
The reason for the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations by the participants were made with minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They're inevitable after the election.
Elections awaken party passions, which then go extinct.
That's good".
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one's for this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make it appear they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is increased optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that a period of disagreement was likely and even inevitable.
"After the things that must be done are done, psychology will in the short term reverse the situation to a confrontation", he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civilization can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012", he said.
The motives have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of overstating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health care law.
These lines of support are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and increasing some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own judgment, have forcibly introduced the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will occur next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama over budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch the reaction of the people closely.
Anyone who thinks he's losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization today are greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked US document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
The city is controlled by a "cleptocracy", leaving a portion of the bribes and protection money it collects directly to the Kremlin, the US Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service operate huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical authority", takes its share as money rises in scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and he blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested corruption, he said: "It's crazy, it's a joke, it's a nuisance".
According to surveys, Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find detailed details, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for diplomats from a foreign country to do that.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government to crime have led some to call it 'dysfunctional,' and to claim that the government operates more like a kleptocracy than a government", the memo states.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term from the criminal and mafia world that literally means 'roof' or protection) that crosses the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all sectors of the Moscow city government bureaucracy.
"Analysts identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow".
"Luzhkov is at the top".
"SFS, MVD and militia are on the second level".
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level".
"This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas, because the city does not provide some services".
The report claims that the SFS collects money from the biggest companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report stated, "explained that Moscow business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law".
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority".
The report notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly find their businesses closed for one reason or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has admitted that little progress has been made.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust bureaucrats", Georgy Satarov, director of Indem's Moscow expert group, said in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy".
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia".
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked least corrupt).
The disclosure of the US embassy note, which did not occur until late at night Moscow time, will surely cause displeasure within the Russian government, and although Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that the WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation claiming that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policies in this country", he said.
"But to be honest with you, we don't suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it was done in such an immoral way".
Red Khmer veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom with stained and peeled walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School recalled the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everybody here loves Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader and cared about his people", said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to face publicly those who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook here that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodian court issued the first conviction of a former member of the Khmer Rouge, sentencing the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Anlong Veng Red Khmer, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they can't do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil".
"This is generating divisions within families".
During the rule of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the government, culminating in the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the army soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gained little benefit after surrender", said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime".
"They were raised without any concept for doing business".
55-year-old Sor Lim, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting his life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine", he said.
"Ta Mok fed them all".
"But now life is hard because we have to self-sufficient".
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concern here.
Early next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases beyond those four.
This didn't help much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district head in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that is thought to have killed thousands of forced labourers.
During a recent stormy afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden pilots on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She claimed that if the court summoned her she would not appear.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable", he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But confronting the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk, of the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces", he said.
"It is our duty to gather these broken pieces together so that we can understand".
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's high school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
Like most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's connection to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But her parents reacted skeptically when she took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the courtroom", he said.
"They have suspicions because they're unsure of how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too much weed and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black soot covered by an oxide-plated roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman by the side of the road, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him", he said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day she decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot's last rest, where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of good luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its weapons-grade uranium reserve
In a surprise victory for President Obama's campaign to protect nuclear material worldwide, the Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will give up its highly enriched uranium reserve, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a security summit.
For years, the US government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and it seemed they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that a couple of classified operations with Belarus were conducted in the last two months, to remove 84.82 kg of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This set the stage for Wednesday's agreement to remove the remaining material, approximately 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke anonymously due to the confidentiality of the matter.
The agreement appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit".
"This shows that this process is working", said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear security.
Clinton said the agreement is "a very significant and important step" taken by Belarus.
In April 2009, Obama pledged in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide over the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be seventh.
A dozen countries did it under the George W. Bush administration.
At the time of Obama's Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have preserved highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically weapons-grade uranium) and low-enriched uranium", Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell them to anyone".
"We use it for research purposes, that's all".
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating an interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said the first task of removing uranium from Belarus in October was particularly difficult, as the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded on a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was carried out by plane.
The US government spent $13 million on the tasks, and most of the money was used to supply Belarus with the research facility with low-enriched uranium, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an Energy Department official working on Global Threat Reduction, said "this was coordinated and orchestrated very carefully to strengthen trust" that led to the Clinton-signed agreement.
The James Martin Center for Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will seek to eliminate its reserve by 2012, according to the Joint Declaration.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of Lukashenko's harsh crackdown on human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggested a potential detachment.
It stated that "while welcoming progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains a central issue for improving bilateral relations, and is essential for the progress of the country and its citizens".
