How should we interpret these movements?
Go ahead, Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with the one of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, speculation in Germany is beginning to emerge about the three possible outcomes to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second is the recovery of the framework, although it now seems science fiction, with a very favorable opinion stream, close to 50% of the population.
The third is a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines on the countries that have infringed, possible suspensions of payments of any of them and the extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government took a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed needed to be done (fiscal rigidity and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second one was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended the rescue decision of Greece.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism at the time, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the Greek bailout.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel is once again emerging with a clear position, demanding reform of the EU treaties to make saving a country possible while also forcing private lenders to bear some of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But their proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should be attending the Union's reform process that will make it possible to take those measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although measures must now be taken with which he may not agree, from that date on the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary area, where countries that infringe will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves in default and, in that case, the private sector will also bear some of the cost.
Germany is pointing out that we must follow a strong path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, is simply not going to be tolerated.
The invitation is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand.
It is not just a matter of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these circumstances is fool ourselves.
I hope the current turmoil will give way to more tranquility.
And let's take advantage of the window of opportunity they've given us, until the spring of 2013.
