The allegedly urged expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether such behaviour is or is not anti-sport and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes to go before the game (which their team had clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in making foul tracks to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will be the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction in the next league match, against Auxerre, and can pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, Jose Mourinho, with two matches and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the football world.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten, but followed rules, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the case is due to the fact that it was starring a team from the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which has sometimes fined its players for similar acts in the past) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technical.
In any event, the debate is whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulations, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether such actions are fraudulent; indeed, they are actions respectful of the rules of sport, but seem to evade their meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the assets of the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to by clean play is preventing the team of offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not fit into what we normally describe as a trap or fraud of the law, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders gain in the deliberate failures examined.
It seems necessary to note that the competition is not disadvantaged or profitable in the same match, as the result of the action is obviously to leave the team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, as the team can be eliminated at the first change, and in addition with this action the players meet a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the card accumulation suspension occurs with a lower one than in the first round.
So, going through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions are not against the spirit of sport, which includes making strategic decisions that will help to make the most of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping or escaping punishment.
Although the line between wit and law fraud is blurred, I think this time it was a clear case of wit.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the guideline to provoke them was transmitted.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
