EU changes to visa rules
The visa applicant must visit the Visa Applicant Service before the interview in the Consular Section; the cost and waiting time will be lower.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicants Service (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff shall take the biometric information of the applicant, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer will there be a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another payment for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with a request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for business and investor visas.
Those wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants requiring a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay there less than in the past.
Also, those applying for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
