Quebec radio host Stéphane Dupont has suffered some setbacks at the Canadian Council of Radio-television Standards (CCNR) over controversial statements about social assistance and about Haitians, as well as his rude language on radio.
The CCNR considers that Mr Dupont and his team at CHOI 98,1 FM had the right to express their opinion, but certain statements contained "incorrect information about social assistance, unduly negative representation of Haitians and rude language that should not be used in broadcasts broadcast during the day".
The Council also noted that discussions on suicide, including the disclosure of the names of two people who had committed suicide, do not violate broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints in relation to comments made on broadcast emissions between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint from the Quebec Social Assistance People's Common Front.
The group complained that the amounts mentioned in the issue were incorrect.
The presenters must communicate reliable data and not misleading data.
In relation to the suicide, the presenter Stéphane Dupont had stated that suicide was an act of cowardice.
Most of the Committee members have concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be considered a solution to life's problems.
'The majority of the Committee considers that the questionable episodes of Dupont le midi have dealt with a sensitive issue in a fair and appropriate manner.'
The Commission has therefore rejected any blame in this respect.
The last litigation concerned statements made after the earthquake in Haiti.
At the time, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had been in a media confrontation that had sparked numerous reactions.
The CHOI presenter stated that he had not made any donations to help Haitians because he could not know for sure whether the needy would actually receive the money.
The Committee considers that these comments are not abusive, but that their cumulative effect is an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already served my three-day suspension up there".
"My file has been clean for a year and a half", the presenter declared.
In all its decisions, the Committee denounces the use of rude language.
In any event, the CHOI-FM radio station has collaborated "even more than required".
The consequences will be minimal for the broadcaster, which must, inter alia, announce the decisions once at the peak hours within three days.
A king of kung fu in Montreal
The Montreal-born Algerian Nacereddine Zemmal has had an extremely peculiar journey.
The athlete, who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and Thai boxing, climbs the world's tatamis and rings in search of new challenges.
"I started practicing martial arts like kung fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria", explained Zemmal, who has lived in the metropolis since 2008 to advance at the professional level.
"In my case, I look for fights everywhere because, for those who don't enjoy the game on the ground that mixed martial arts involves, there are few competitions in North America".
The athlete, who works as a security officer and employee of UPS, recently gave bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) World Amateur Championship, held from October 23 to 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I won in the full contact kickboxing and Thai boxing categories", he explained.
"I'm currently preparing to participate in the World Cup of San Shou in China".
"They will invite athletes who have finished in the top four at the last world championship in each category".
"In 2009, I won the bronze medal in Toronto".
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished eighth".
"In 2007, in China, I finished fifth, but I came in third in Toronto in 2009", he added.
"The interesting thing is I've been making progress in every competition".
"At this step, I'll be the first this time or next year!"
San shou or sanda is a Chinese discipline in which punching with fists and feet is allowed, as well as throwing opponents to the ground.
The clashes were originally held on a platform and, less often, in a ring.
The most famous fighter in this type of combat is the Vietnamese-American Cung Le, widely recognized in the martial arts world.
Although Born Zemmal must only keep a competition in his career, he will undoubtedly attend the great "King of Sanda" tournament, the Super Bowl of kung-fu.
"This competition is the most famous and prestigious in China", explains the friendly boy.
"It's like the equivalent of the Lumpinee Stadium (the biggest stadium in Thailand) ".
"It's been an amazing experience".
Zemmal has won his first fight, in the semifinals of his category (80 kg), but lost in the final.
"The one who won me is a real professional", he says.
'There are four competitors per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg).'
"The winners of the semifinals face each other at the end of their category".
"Then the champions of each category compete to crown a single champion, the king of kung fu".
450 million in contracts without tender
Hydro-Québec has awarded direct contracts worth $450 million to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this flood of more than 100 contracts is a consortium of BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained the largest contract, the project management contract, for a sum of 295 million without a previous tender.
The consortium, called Énergie gérance, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec's decision to entrust the private sector with the responsibility of managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the energy management consortium obtained the lucrative contract without a public tender having been previously held.
For the Quebec Party, the use of business consortia poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and lead to a rise in prices.
"It's a new method of collusion and eliminating competition".
"That is, people, instead of doing it in secret, now do it openly", said yesterday the Quebec Party deputy Sylvain Simard at a press conference.
Earlier this morning Mr Simard raised the question in the National Assembly because he said he did not understand how the public interest could be benefited in this way.
Natural Resources Minister Nathalie Normandeau responded in the afternoon, firmly denying any collusion with this contract.
"I'm starting to get tired", he protested, arguing that the PQ had acted "unfairly" and "with a lack of rigor".
He said the "minimum" would be for PQ to apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice throughout the world.
It is usually a time-limited partnership that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project has a high level of complexity, taking into account the scale of the works.
The works have already begun and will last until 2012.
In all cases, the contract was awarded without competition being involved; it was a negotiation.
In addition, the consortium formula has ceased to be the exception to the rule in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the formula for consortia in the technical advisory sector is undergoing government investigation.
A quick look at Quebec's trade register identifies more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be permanent.
Dessau thus works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal entity, Dessau.
As regards the Énergie gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau has stressed that "the James Bay area responds to a particular labour dynamic and Hydro-Québec has responded specifically to it since the 1970s".
The main head of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has given an explanation which highlights the fact that the project management contract has been awarded directly.
"If you answer a bid and there are few participants, your prices are going to be higher".
"You have two options: you can contact the players in the sector and tell them: we'll negotiate a satisfactory deal and a good price".
"The idea is, however, that what matters is not the price, but the competition of the people", Mr Laporte noted.
