A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in a hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of a series of major concrete projects the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still hold 50 to 70% of the market, were replaced by fluorescent bulbs or, even better, by light-emitting diode (DEL or "LED") bulbs, much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from the planet's fleet of cars.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitter countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that amount should be further reduced to stabilise, before 2020, the rise in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from spiraling out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the rest, that is, 5% produces light.
In the case of fluorocompact lamps, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED lamps, energy consumption is reduced even more than twice.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
New LED bulbs, such as those launched by Philips this week (a company that also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a flashlight, giving us an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be implemented in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostats and emit very little heat.
On top of that, they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have expressed reservations about fluorocompact bulbs, which contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report notes, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not fluorescent bulbs but coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted on incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants costing 2.5 billion to build.
