Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks thing has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" US revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculous profile of Khadafi has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The norm that secret files should only be made up of publicly known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news on the non-existent), but because those who engage in occultism not only trust what they already know, which reaffirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know, the editor of Libération) is lazy (or has little desire), who only considers true what he can acknowledge.
Top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek report the week before.
So why have the disclosures of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they are just saying what every educated person knows already, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of State can call or fly to dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited representation exercises, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows perfectly well, only we pretend we don't know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad impression of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can access the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both victims and "dwarfs".
But let's get into the true nature of what happened.
In the days of Orwell, he could be thought of as a mighty Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that not even the secrets of power can escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the citizens' avenger) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all her power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information online, as it would be like posting it on a street sign.
But it is also clear that with current technologies, you cannot expect to keep confidential conversations on the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of his counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and therefore novel, but I imagine government agents who travel discreetly on diligently uncontrollable routes, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at best, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then stored in a single copy in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I've written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has again created a cable telegraph (telephone).
Video tapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the setup, whereas now digital CDs only allow for moving forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, in enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, whereas by plane, with the travel that comes with it, we need three and a half hours.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication techniques to bring us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was being secretly plotted in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: France's splashes in its pledges of financing
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (called fast start or early start) made by developed countries have been met.
And the French splashes have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has committed to contribute EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. 420 million a year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures taken by its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was a remarkable achievement and was appreciated for what it really was worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, money must be 'new and additional' to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed a harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, each person chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added over three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
France, on the other hand, considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, it does not refer to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) as long as it is intended to respect its commitment to 'new and additional' funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that every euro borrowed equals a donated euro.
This is obviously difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emission reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro to be recovered as the equivalent of a euro given... At most, only the cost of the loan to the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France finds this reasoning unhelpful: it "respects" its €420 million commitment by making 91.5% of loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (€36.1 million); see the EU document for your own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other hand, in relation to the actual financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", just as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been the arbitrator) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a brief, relatively short-term, detail of the whole climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of sand in the huge machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012 with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could advance the debate on the stakes in long-term financing (another essential chapter being discussed at present): we will not get rid of the question of the 'additional character' or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore hope that the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its view of the 'additional character' and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning against pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (the old rights and respect movement for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistical significance given the limited number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problematic treatment", purchased in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food that a ten-year-old child typically consumes at four meals and one tentempié a day.
These model meals, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruit and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as candy, were tested in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the table is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Centre for Cancer Research.
"Although in virtually all cases the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE pollutants is of concern", the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible cancer residues and three considered safe cancer residues, as well as about a dozen residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a school tent tent, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the Kenyan green juveniles, included in the food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even bread or gum were all adhered to pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon rod was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The end-risk of these "polluting cocktails" to consumers "is likely to be underestimated", says the study.
The European Ecology-Green Alliance (EE-LV) has proposed that, "in view of the gravity of the situation", a moratorium on the use of pesticides be applied to curb "the rise of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of 365 different pesticide residues identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 were in cereals.
